Kingdom}}<sup>1</sup><ref>Including Anguilla, Cayman Islands, Montserrat, and Turks and Caicos Islands</ref>\n*{{flag|United States}}<sup>1</sup>\n*{{flag|Uruguay}}<sup>3</sup>\n*{{flag|Uzbekistan}}\n*{{flag|Vanuatu}}<sup>3</sup>\n*{{flag|Vatican City}}\n*{{flag|Venezuela}}\n*{{flag|Vietnam}}\n*{{flag|Zambia}}\n*{{flag|Zimbabwe}}\n|\n|}\n\n<div class=\"font-size:smaller\">Note: As of June 2018, the visa fee for citizens of:\n*countries with mark \"1\" is US$100\n*countries with mark \"2\" is US$25\n*countries with mark \"3\" is US$0\n*countries without any mark is US$80\n</div>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align: left; font-size: smaller; table-layout: fixed\"\n!Date of e-visa eligibility\n|-\n|\n*27 November 2014: Australia, Brazil, Cambodia, Djibouti, Fiji, Finland, Germany, Indonesia, Israel, Japan, Jordan, Kenya, Kiribati, Laos, Luxembourg, Marshall Islands, Mauritius, Mexico, Micronesia, Myanmar, Nauru, New Zealand (including Cook Islands and Niue), Norway, Oman, Palau, Palestine, Papua New Guinea, Philippines, Russia, Samoa, Singapore, Solomon Islands, South Korea, Thailand, Tonga, Tuvalu, Ukraine, United Arab Emirates, United States, Vanuatu, Vietnam<ref>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=113349 ETA enabled Visa on Arrival Scheme], [[Press Information Bureau]], [[Government of India]], 15 December 2014.</ref>\n*January 2015: Guyana<ref>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=117009 TVoAs in February 2015 show an increase of 1162% over the TVoAs of February 2014], [[Press Information Bureau]], [[Government of India]], 13 March 2015.</ref>\n*14 April 2015: Sri Lanka<ref>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=116947 Prime Minister's media statement during visit to Sri Lanka], [[Press Information Bureau]], [[Government of India]], 13 March 2015.</ref>\n*1 May 2015: Antigua and Barbuda, Bahamas, Barbados, Belize, Canada, Chile, Costa Rica, Dominica, Dominican Republic, Ecuador, El Salvador, Estonia, France, Georgia, Grenada, Haiti, Honduras, Latvia, Liechtenstein, Lithuania, Montenegro, Nicaragua, North Macedonia, Paraguay, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Vatican City, and British Overseas Territories citizens of Anguilla, Cayman Islands and Montserrat<ref>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=120017 Extension of e-Tourist Visa scheme to 31 more countries], [[Press Information Bureau]], [[Government of India]], 29 April 2015.</ref>\n*30 July 2015: China, Hong Kong, Macau<ref>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=123908 Extension of e-Tourist Visa scheme to China, Hong Kong and Macau from tomorrow], [[Press Information Bureau]], [[Government of India]], 29 July 2015.</ref>\n*15 August 2015: Andorra, Argentina, Armenia, Belgium, Bolivia, Colombia, Cuba, East Timor, Guatemala, Hungary, Ireland, Jamaica, Malaysia, Malta, Monaco, Mongolia, Mozambique, Netherlands (including Aruba), Panama, Peru, Poland, Portugal, Saint Lucia, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, Seychelles, Slovenia, Spain, Suriname, Sweden, Taiwan, Tanzania, United Kingdom, Uruguay, Venezuela, and British Overseas Territories citizens of Turks and Caicos Islands<ref>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=124631 Government extends e-Tourist Visa scheme to 36 more countries and 7 more airports from August 15, 2015], [[Press Information Bureau]], [[Government of India]], 7 August 2015.</ref>\n*26 February 2016: Albania, Austria, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Botswana, Brunei, Bulgaria, Cape Verde, Comoros, Croatia, Czech Republic, Denmark, Eritrea, Gabon, Gambia, Ghana, Greece, Guinea, Iceland, Ivory Coast, Lesotho, Liberia, Madagascar, Malawi, Moldova, Namibia, Romania, San Marino, Senegal, Serbia, Slovakia, South Africa, Swaziland, Switzerland, Tajikistan, Trinidad and Tobago, Zambia, Zimbabwe<ref>[http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=136761 Extension of e-Tourist Visa scheme to 37 more countries from tomorrow], [[Press Information Bureau]], [[Government of India]], 25 February 2016.</ref>\n*1 April 2017: Angola, Azerbaijan, Burundi, Cameroon, Cyprus, Italy, Mali, Niger, Rwanda, Sierra Leone, Uzbekistan\n*July 2017: Uganda<ref>[http://hci.gov.in/kampala/?pdf6219?000 Press release], High Commission of India in Kampala, 11 July 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/now-e-visa-facility-for-uganda/article19274137.ece Now, e-visa facility for Uganda], [[The Hindu]], 14 July 2017.</ref>\n*5 March 2018: Kazakhstan<ref name=kz>[http://www.indembastana.in/news_detail/?newsid=196 India Extends the Facility of e-Visa to the Nationals of Kazakhstan]</ref>\n*26 April 2018: Kyrgyzstan<ref name=kg>[https://akipress.com/news:605677 E-visa facility now available for Kyrgyz nationals for travel to India]</ref>\n*23 August 2018: Qatar<ref name=qa>[https://www.gulf-times.com/story/603699/India-adds-Qatar-to-list-of-countries-eligible-for-e-visa India adds Qatar to list of countries eligible for e-visa]</ref>\n*17 June 2019: Saudi Arabia<ref name=sa>[http://www.indianembassy.org.sa/consular/visa Visa], Embassy of India in Riyadh.</ref>\n*October 2019: Belarus, Benin\n|}\n\n==Reform==\n\n===2013===\nIn October 2013, India decided to initiate the process of extending visa-on-arrival access to 40 more nations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.in.msn.com/national/visa-on-arrival-for-40-more-nations|title=Visa on arrival for 40 more nations |website=MSN News |accessdate=17 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029203201/http://news.in.msn.com/national/visa-on-arrival-for-40-more-nations|archive-date=29 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In January 2014, plans were confirmed by [[Minister of State for Parliamentary Affairs and Planning|Minister of State for Parliamentary Affairs and Planning of India]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-01-08/news/45991577_1_arrival-facility-40-more-countries-tourism-ministry-data | title=Visa on arrival for 40 more countries to be a reality soon | date=8 January 2014 |newspaper=The Economic Times |accessdate=19 January 2016}}</ref> The sixteen different types of visa would also be reduced to three: work, business and tourism.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/business-24491344/india-revamps-visa-system-to-boost-visitor-numbers|title=Indian visa system overhauled|date=13 October 2013|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> The proposal initially met resistance from intelligence agencies and the possible problem of queues emerged.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/visa-and-immigration/visa-on-arrival-facility-extended-to-tourists-from-180-countries/articleshow/29921043.cms?intenttarget=no|title=Visa-on-arrival facility extended to tourists from 180 countries|date=6 February 2014|newspaper=The Economic Times|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/mumbai/waiting-time-in-immigration-queues-has-almost-doubled-at-mumbai-airport/story-HUqRoMyniM1P79fVRBE5eJ.html|title=Waiting time in immigration queues \u2018has almost doubled\u2019 at Mumbai airport|date=29 December 2015|newspaper=Hindustan Times |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2014===\nIn February 2014 it was announced that Indian intelligence agencies had given their approval to visa-on-arrival for up to 180 countries, largely due to the new possibilities provided by the [[Immigration, Visa and Foreigners' Registration and Tracking]] (IVFRT) system. The system would not be a typical visa on arrival in order to avoid clutter at the airports, but a system based on a prior online application modelled after Australian [[Electronic Travel Authority (Australia)|Electronic Travel Authority]] system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/intel-nod-for-visa-on-arrival/|title=Intel nod for visa-on-arrival|date=2 February 2014|newspaper=The Indian Express |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/666617/india-set-to-ease-visa-restrictions-pakistani-citizens-not-included-in-the-changes/|title=India set to ease visa restrictions for 180 countries except Pakistan |newspaper=The Express Tribune|date=2 February 2014 |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=India visa-on-arrival scheme to be extended|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-26062351|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=7 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 February 2014 it was decided to introduce visa-on-arrival to tourists from 180 countries. Technical implementation, such as setting up the website for applications, was expected to take about 6 months and the authorities hoped to have it in place for the tourist season beginning in October 2014. Prospective visitors would have to pay a fee and the electronic version of the visa should be granted within three days. The program was expected to apply to all international airports. However, nationals of [[Afghanistan]], [[Iran]], [[Iraq]], [[Nigeria]], [[Pakistan]], [[Somalia]], [[Sudan]] were to be excluded from this program.<ref name=\"zee14\">{{cite news |url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/nation/india-to-extended-visa-on-arrival-to-tourists-from-180-countries_909348.html|title=India to extend visa-on-arrival to tourists from 180 countries|date=5 February 2014|publisher=Zee News |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014 it was announced that India hoped to implement the program for citizens of 40 countries in the first phase by December 2014 and later on for 109 additional countries if the first phase were implemented successfully.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.southasianobserver.com/topstories.php?cid=1205|work=South Asian Observer |title=India to Offer Electronic Visa for Canadians From December |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014 it was revealed that ministries of Tourism, Home Affairs and External Affairs could not agree on the list of countries for the ETA. The [[Ministry of Tourism (India)|Ministry of Tourism]] proposed to allow the new system for the citizens of the 15 countries with the most visitors to India, the [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]] proposed to create a balanced list with some Asian and African countries, while the [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] proposed to exclude all countries with high security concerns.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/E-visa-scheme-hits-inter-departmental-roadblock/articleshow/40445610.cms|title=E-visa scheme hits inter-departmental roadblock |newspaper=The Times of India|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014 Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] announced that the [[United States]] would be added to the list of countries whose citizens may obtain a visa on arrival.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/modi-us-visit-visa-on-arrival-facility-on-anvil-for-us-tourists/|title=Modi US visit: Visa on Arrival facility on anvil for US tourists|date=21 September 2014|website=The Indian Express |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> However, in October 2014 the planned introduction of the new e-Visa system was pushed from 2 October 2014 to June 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/e-visas-may-make-visa-arrival-redundant-says-tourism-minister-naik-1741615.html|title=E-visas may make visa-on-arrival redundant, says Tourism Minister Naik|date=3 October 2014|website=Firstpost |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> It was also revealed that the list of visa on arrival countries was unlikely to be expanded in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/visa-on-arrival-faces-project-infra-hurdle-114100400627_1.html|title=Visa on arrival faces project infra hurdle|first=Arijit|last=Paladhi|date=4 October 2014|newspaper=Business Standard |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014 it was announced that the e-visa system might be rolled out for about 25 countries including the 13 countries that were already eligible for visa on arrival.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/E-visa-system-likely-to-be-rolled-out-next-week/articleshow/44984345.cms|title=E-visa system likely to be rolled out next week |newspaper=The Times of India |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> Later that month it was announced that 28 countries would become eligible for an electronic visa on 27 November 2014 and that the list would include visa on arrival eligible countries as well as [[Brazil]], [[Germany]], [[Israel]], [[Jordan]], [[Mauritius]], [[Norway]], [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], [[Russia]], [[Thailand]], [[Ukraine]], [[United Arab Emirates]], [[United States]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/visa-and-immigration/us-israel-to-be-given-e-visa-facility-from-november-27/articleshow/45149981.cms?intenttarget=no|title=US, Israel to be given e-visa facility from November 27|date=14 November 2014|newspaper=The Economic Times|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/world/us-israel-palestine-to-be-given-e-visa-facility-on-nov-27_1499158.html | title=US, Israel, Palestine to be given e-visa facility on Nov 27 | publisher=Zee News | date=14 November 2014 |accessdate=19 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, the Indian Prime Minister announced visa on arrival facility for nationals of all Pacific countries and Australia.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/narendra-modi-fiji-suva-fiji-parliament-visa-on-arrival/1/402639.html | title=Modi announces visa on arrival for 14 Pacific Island countries | publisher=India Today | date=19 November 2014 |accessdate=19 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/modi-assures-visa-on-arrival-for-australian-tourists/article6608146.ece | title=Modi assures visa on arrival for Australian tourists | date=17 November 2014 |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=19 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2015===\nThe manual processing of the visa on arrival was discontinued in January 2015.<ref name=\"immigrationindia.nic.in\"/> Until 26 January 2015, citizens of the following countries holding ordinary passports were granted visa on arrival without obtaining an ETA (unless they were of Pakistani origin), for a single stay up to 30 days in India when traveling as a tourist or for visiting family or friends:<ref name=\"timatic\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immigrationindia.nic.in/visa_on_arrival2.htm|publisher=Bureau of Immigration (India) |title=Tourist Visa on Arrival |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"immigrationindia.nic.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.immigrationindia.nic.in/content/discontinuation-manual-tvoa-12-nationals-namely-japan-singapore-philippines-finland|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106132647/http://www.immigrationindia.nic.in/content/discontinuation-manual-tvoa-12-nationals-namely-japan-singapore-philippines-finland|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 January 2015|title=Discontinuation of manual TVoA to 12 Nationals namely (Japan, Singapore, Philippines, Finland, Luxembourg, New Zealand, Cambodia, Laos, Vietnam, Myanmar, Indonesia and South Korea) w.e.f. 27.01.15|publisher=|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n{|style=\" {{border-radius|1em}} {{box-shadow|0.1em|0.1em|0.5em|rgba(0,0,0,0.75)}}; background-color: white; border: 1px solid white; padding: 5px;\"\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n|\n*{{flag|Cambodia}}\n*{{flag|Finland}}\n*{{flag|Indonesia}}\n|valign=top|\n*{{flag|Japan}}\n*{{flag|Laos}}\n*{{flag|Luxembourg}}\n|valign=top|\n*{{flag|Myanmar}}\n*{{flag|New Zealand}}\n*{{flag|Philippines}}\n|valign=top|\n*{{flag|Singapore}}\n*{{flag|South Korea}}\n*{{flag|Vietnam}}\n|\n|}\n\nIn February 2015, the [[Ministry of Tourism (India)|Ministry of Tourism]] proposed extending the facility to citizens of [[China]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Spain]], [[France]], [[Italy]] and [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/neGc9LguayHRFddD4Yx7yI/India-may-extend-evisa-facility-to-six-more-countries.html|title=India may extend e-visa facility to six more countries|first=Moulishree|last=Srivastava|date=20 February 2015|newspaper=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]] |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> Subsequently, the [[Minister of Finance (India)|Minister of Finance]] announced that the facility would be extended, in stages, to citizens of 150 countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/visa-and-immigration/budget-2015-government-to-increase-visa-on-arrival-facilities-to-150-countries-says-fm-jaitley/articleshow/46407075.cms|title=Budget 2015: Government to increase visa on arrival facilities to 150 countries, says FM Jaitley|first1=Anirban|last1=Chowdhury|first2=Divya|last2=Sathyanarayanan|date=28 February 2015|newspaper=The Economic Times|accessdate=17 September 2017|}}</ref> In March 2015 it was announced that 53 nations were shortlisted for the second round of expansion of the system based on the number of tourist arrivals in the previous years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/53-nations-to-get-nod-for-e-visa-soon-115031000058_1.html|title=53 nations to get nod for e-visa soon|first=Arijit|last=Paladhi|date=10 March 2015|newspaper=Business Standard|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Government was criticised for naming the new policy \"Visa on arrival\" it decided to rename it to \"e-Tourist Visa (eTV)\" in April 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/to-end-confusion-e-visa-scheme-renamed-visa-online-753577|title=It's Not Visa-on-Arrival, Cedes Government, Scheme to be Renamed|publisher=NDTV |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/visa-and-immigration/govt-decides-to-rename-its-e-visa-scheme-to-visa-online/articleshow/46863822.cms|title=Govt decides to rename its e-visa scheme to 'Visa Online'|date=9 April 2015|newspaper=The Economic Times|accessdate=17 September 2017|}}</ref>\n\nThe e-Tourist Visa facility was extended to 31 new countries on 1 May 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/e-tourist-visa-scheme-extended-to-31-more-countries-115042901141_1.html|title=e-Tourist Visa scheme extended to 31 more countries|agency=Press Trust of India|date=29 April 2015|newspaper=Business Standard|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Indian Foreign Ministry]] announced that Chinese citizens will be able to apply for e-Tourist Visa facility in order to coordinate Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] visiting China between 14 and 16 May. Disputes about the [[Sino-Indian border dispute|Sino-Indian border]] and national security would be postponed.<ref name=\"CHN\">{{cite news |title=Govt may snub agencies, clear e-visa for Chinese|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Govt-may-snub-agencies-clear-e-visa-for-Chinese/articleshow/47195986.cms|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 July 2015 [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Indian Ministry of Home Affairs]] announced the extension of e-Tourist Visa facility to [[China]], [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] with effect from 30 July 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=123908|title=Extension of e-Tourist Visa scheme to China, Hong Kong and Macau from tomorrow|website=pib.nic.in|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe list of eligible nationalities was extended with 36 new countries on 15 August 2015. On the same day the list of eTV airports was expanded with 7 new airports.<ref name=\"extension\">{{cite web|url=https://indianvisaonline.gov.in/visa/Press_Note_extension_to_36_countries.pdf|title=Indian Visa Application|website=indianvisaonline.gov.in|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> The extension to 150 nationalities was scheduled to be finished by 31 March 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/visa-and-immigration/e-tourist-visa-to-be-extended-to-150-countries-by-march-31/articleshow/48487294.cms | title=E-tourist visa to be extended to 150 countries by March 31 | date=14 August 2015 |newspaper=The Economic Times |accessdate=19 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015 it was announced that the list would be expanded by another 37 countries.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/e-visa-facility-to-be-extended-to-37-more-countries/articleshow/48936601.cms|title=e-visa facility to be extended to 37 more countries |newspaper=The Times of India |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nIn January 2016 it was announced that the extension would take place by March 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/nri/visa-and-immigration/govt-on-track-to-extend-e-tourist-visa-facility-to-150-nations/articleshow/50458987.cms|title=Govt on track to extend e-tourist visa facility to 150 nations|date=17 September 2017|newspaper=The Economic Times |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> In November 2015 it was announced that the visa validity will be extended to 180 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buyingbusinesstravel.com/news/0424909-india-extends-e-visa-scheme|title=India extends e-Visa scheme|website=buyingbusinesstravel.com|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016 it was announced that the multiple entries would become available and that e-Tourist Visa holders would receive a gift pack on arrival.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/govt-mulls-new-e-visa-rules-multiple-visits-180-day-validity-in-the-pipeline/|title=Govt mulls new e-visa rules: Multiple visits, 180-day validity in the pipeline|date=15 January 2016|newspaper=The Indian Express |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe eTV list was extended for tourists from 37 more countries on 26 February 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/now-evisa-for-tourists-from-37-more-nations/article8282462.ece|title=Now, e-visa for tourists from 37 more nations|first1=National|last1=Bureau|first2=National|last2=Bureau|date=26 February 2016|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016 it was announced that the electronic visa scheme would be reformed to include 27 visa codes denoting various visit purposes such as tourism, business or medical visits.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/e-tourist-visa-scheme-coding-purpose-of-visit-government-3008897/|title=Govt plans to modify e-tourist visa scheme, bring in coding|date=2 September 2016 |newspaper=The Indian Express |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> It was also announced that the list of visa on arrival eligible countries would be expanded.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Now-citizens-of-more-nations-set-to-get-visa-on-arrival/articleshow/53971734.cms|title=Now, citizens of more nations set to get visa on arrival |newspaper=The Times of India |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 November 2016 the Government of India approved further liberalization, simplification and rationalization of visa regime in India. It also announced that more countries would be added to the e-visa list.<ref name=added2017>[http://tourismbreakingnews.com/e-visa-now-applicable-to-158-countries/ 8 countries added to e-visa list], Tourism Breaking News, December 5, 2016.</ref> The e-visa would have a validity of 60 days and could be applied for by foreign nationals up to four months ahead of the visit.<ref>[http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/55722289.cms Government approves new visa policy to attract foreigners, boost trade], The Economic Times, December 1, 2016.</ref> Five seaports \u2013 Mumbai, Kochi, Chennai, Goa and Mangalore \u2013 would receive tourists coming with e-visa.<ref>[http://www.ptinews.com/news/8140411_Five-seaports-to-receive-tourists-with-e-Visa.html Five seaports to receive tourists with e-Visa], Press Trust of India, December 1, 2016.</ref>\n\n===2017===\nFrom 1 April 2017 e-visas are granted under three categories of tourist, business and medical. The window for application under e-visa scheme was increased from 30 days to 120 days, and duration of stay on e-visa was increased from 30 days to 60 days, with double entry on e-tourist and e-business visa, and triple entry on e-medical visa.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/new-e-visa-regime-comes-into-effect-from-april-1-to-boost-inflow-of-tourists/articleshow/57947825.cms|title=New e-visa regime comes into effect from April 1, to boost inflow of tourists |newspaper=The Times of India |accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> The list of eligible nationalities was also further expanded with 11 new countries,<ref name=added2017 /> and the list of arrival ports was increased from 16 to 24 airports and 3 seaports.<ref name=evisa />\n\nIn July 2017 [[Uganda]] was added to the list of e-Visa eligible countries.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/now-e-visa-facility-for-uganda/article19274137.ece|title=Now, e-visa facility for Uganda|first1=Vijaita|last1=Singh|first2=Vijaita|last2=Singh|date=14 July 2017|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nDuring 2018, [[Kazakhstan]], [[Kyrgyzstan]] and [[Qatar]] were added to the list of e-Visa eligible countries.<ref name=kz/><ref name=kg/><ref name=qa/>\n\n===2019===\nIn January 2019 the Indian government updated e-Visa rules for all eligible countries. The validity of Indian e-tourist and e-Business Visa was increased from 60 days with double entry to up-to 1 year with multiple entries. The validity count starts from the day of being granted the e-visa online and not from the day of physical entry as before.<ref>{{cite web |title=Indian e-Visa |url=https://indianvisaonline.gov.in/evisa/tvoa.html |website=indianvisaonline.gov.in}}</ref>\n\nFor e-tourist visa, continuous stay during each visit shall not exceed 90 days for all eligible nationals of e-tourist visa except for nationals of US, UK, Japan and Canada. For nationals of US, UK, Japan and Canada, continuous stay during each visit should not exceed 180 days. No [[Foreigner registration in India|FRRO]] (Foreigners Regional Registration Officer) registration is required.\n\nFor e-business visa, continuous stay during each visit should not exceed 180 days for nationals of all countries who are eligible for grant of e-business visa and no [https://indianfrro.gov.in/eservices/home.jsp FRRO] (Foreigners Regional Registration Officer) registration is required if the stay is for less than 180 days.\n\nDuring 2019, [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Belarus]] and [[Benin]] were added to the list of e-Visa eligible countries.<ref name=sa/>\n\nIn August 2019, Indian Government announced a 30 Day Visa during the peak season for 25 Dollars.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/india-to-offer-30-day-e-tourist-visa-for-25-during-peak-season-1582611-2019-08-20 |date=20 August 2019 |title=India to offer 30-day e-tourist visa for $25 during peak season |website=India Today |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Costs for visa applications==\nVisa applications can be submitted in person or sent by post to an [[List of diplomatic missions of India|Indian consulate]]. It can also be submitted to designated Visa service provider in certain countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indian Embassy in US outsources Indian Visa Services to Cox & Kings|url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/05/indian-embassy-in-us-outsources-indian-visa-services-to-cox-kings/|work=IANS|publisher=news.biharprabha.com|accessdate=8 May 2014}}</ref> Costs differ per consulate and region. Some visa-handling services charge a small fee in addition, to check that completed application form meets all requirements and submit the documents on the applicant's behalf.<ref>[http://hippie-inheels.com/step-step-how-to-apply-for-indian-tourist-visa-from-usa/ Step by Step: How to Apply for Indian Tourist Visa from USA], Hippie in Heels, August 18, 2014.</ref>\n\nCitizens of the following countries do not pay a visa fee \u2013 Argentina, Cook Islands, Fiji, Indonesia, Jamaica, Kiribati, Marshall Islands, Mauritius, Micronesia, Myanmar, Nauru, Niue Island, Palau, Papua New Guinea, Samoa, Seychelles, Solomon Island, South Africa, Tonga, Tuvalu, Uruguay and Vanuatu.<ref name=\"e-Tourist Visa Fee\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/india-to-grant-free-visa-to-myanmar-citizens-modi/article19630531.ece|title=India to grant free visa to Myanmar citizens: Modi|date=6 September 2017|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Restricted and protected area permits==\n\nA [[Protected Area Permit]] (PAP) is required to enter the states of [[Arunachal Pradesh]] and [[Sikkim]] and some parts of the states of [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[Rajasthan]] and [[Uttarakhand]]. A [[Restricted Area Permit]] (RAP) is required to enter the [[Andaman and Nicobar Islands]] and parts of [[Sikkim]]. Some of these requirements are occasionally lifted for a year at a time. Permits are not required for nationals of [[Bhutan]] travelling by air to/from [[Thimphu]] via [[Bagdogra]] and for nationals of [[Nepal]] travelling by air to/from [[Kathmandu]] (if travelling by land a pass issued by either the Foreigners Regional Registration Office, Superintendent of police or the diplomatic representation of India in Bhutan or Nepal is required).<ref name=\"timatic\" /> Special permits are needed to enter [[Lakshadweep]] Islands. [[Maldivian people|Maldivian citizens]] are allowed to visit [[Minicoy]] island for fifteen days if allowed by the High Commissioner of India to the [[Maldives]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://cruisingmaldives.blog/2017/11/28/minicoy-an-indian-island-as-close-to-maldives-as-you-can-get/ |title=Minicoy, an Indian Island as Close to Maldives as You Can Get |date=2017-11-28 |website=Cruising Maldives|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref>\n\n==Pakistani passport holders and persons of Pakistani origin==\nPersons who ever held Pakistani citizenship, or who have a parent or spouse that held Pakistani citizenship are ineligible for India's new E-Visa scheme, and so must apply to their local Indian mission for visas. Applicants who once held Pakistani citizenship require lengthy processing times, while foreign spouses and those of Pakistani origin who never held Pakistani citizenship typically experience shorter processing times.<ref name=\"india.org.pk\"/> India also forbids Pakistani applicants with dual nationality from applying on their non-Pakistani passport.<ref name=\"india.org.pk\"/>\n\n===Visa on arrival for persons over 65 years of age===\nAs of 31 March 2013, Pakistani citizens over the age of 65 with the sole objective of meeting friends or family are granted a 45-day visa upon arrival at the Attari-Wagah Checkpoint, so long as the applicant provides a sponsorship certificate from their contacts in India attesting that they will be responsible for the visit of their Pakistani friend or relative, and which must also be countersigned by a DM, SP, SDM, Tehsildar, BDO, SHO, Groups A officer of State and Central Government, or principal/headmaster of a government college or government school who attest that they personally know the sponsor.<ref name=\"india.org.pk\">[http://www.india.org.pk/pages.php?id=133 Visa on Arrival], High Commission of India in Pakistan.</ref> This scheme does not apply to those who wish to visit [[Punjab]], [[Kerala]] and Restricted Areas, nor does it apply to those who have ever been denied an Indian visa before.<ref name=\"india.org.pk\"/>\n\n==Diplomatic or official passports==\n[[File:Visa policy of India for holders of diplomatic and service category passports.png|600px|right|thumbnail|Visa policy for diplomatic or official passport holders{{legend|#118611|India}}{{legend|#09098D|Visa-free for diplomatic and official passport holders}}{{legend|#F69336|Visa-free for diplomatic passports}}{{legend|#ABABAB|Visa required for diplomatic or official passports holders}}]]\n\nHolders of diplomatic or service category passports of the following countries do not require a visa for India \u2013 Albania, Argentina, Azerbaijan, Bahrain, Bangladesh, Belarus, Belize, Brazil, Brunei, Bulgaria, Cambodia, Chile, Colombia, Croatia, Cyprus, Denmark, Ecuador, Egypt, El Salvador, Eswatini, Georgia, Guatemala, Guyana, Honduras, Hungary, Indonesia, Israel, Ivory Coast, Jordan, Kazakhstan, Kuwait, Kyrgyzstan, Laos, Malaysia, Maldives, Mauritius, Mexico, Mongolia, Morocco, Mozambique, Myanmar, Namibia, Nicaragua, Palestine, Panama, Paraguay, Peru, Philippines, Qatar, Russia, Rwanda, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Serbia, Singapore, South Africa, South Korea, Sri Lanka, Suriname, Syria, Tajikistan, Tanzania, Thailand, Tunisia, Uganda, United Arab Emirates, Uruguay, Venezuela and Vietnam and diplomatic passports only of the following countries \u2013 Afghanistan, Armenia, Botswana, Cuba, Czech Republic, France, Germany, Greece, Iran, Italy, Japan, Kenya, Latvia, Lithuania, Malta, North Macedonia, Norway, Poland, Portugal, Romania, Slovenia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, Turkey, Turkmenistan, Ukraine, Uzbekistan, Zambia.<ref name=\"timatic\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mea.gov.in/bvwa.htm|title=MEA - MEA : Visa Waiver Agreements|website=mea.gov.in|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIndia signed visa waiver agreements for holders of diplomatic, special and official passports with the following countries, which are yet to come into force:\n\n*Ghana \u2014 13 June 2016<ref>https://www.mea.gov.in/TreatyDetail.htm?2500</ref>\n*Oman \u2014 11 February 2018<ref>[https://mea.gov.in/Images/attach/Oman.pdf]</ref>\n*Zimbabwe (diplomatic passports only) \u2014 3 November 2018<ref>https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/venkiah-naidu-meets-zimbabwe-president-signs-6-agreements-1942478</ref>\n*Malawi \u2013 5 November 2018<ref>https://www.aninews.in/news/world/asia/india-malawi-ink-3-mous201811060153310001/</ref>\n*Bahamas \u2013 29 November 2018<ref>{{cite tweet |user=MOFABahamas |number=1068180430980026368 |date=29 November 2018 |title=MOFA Bahamas @MOFABahamas H A P P E N I N G  N O W Signing of Visa Waiver Agreement for Holders of Diplomatic and Official Passports. Bahamas and India}}</ref>\n*Algeria \u2013 February 2019<ref>{{cite tweet |user=indiainalgeria |number=1091047844474245121 |date=31 January 2019 |title=Au cours de la visite, deux documents ont \u00e9t\u00e9 sign\u00e9s : (1) un Programme d\u2019\u00c9change Culturel et (2) un accord d\u2019exemption de visa pour les d\u00e9tenteurs de passeports diplomatiques et officiels. (3/3)}}</ref>\n*Bolivia \u2013 March 2019<ref>[http://www.newsonair.com/Main-News-Details.aspx?id=361587]</ref>\n*Costa Rica \u2013 March 2019<ref>https://www.mea.gov.in/TreatyDetail.htm?3556</ref>\n*Benin \u2013 29 July 2019<ref>https://mea.gov.in/Images/amb1/Benin_text.pdf</ref>\n*Estonia (diplomatic passports only) \u2013 21 August 2019<ref>[https://mea.gov.in/Images/amb1/estonia_text.pdf]</ref>\n*Dominican Republic \u2013 August 2019\n\n== Visa types ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+VISA PROVISION\n!Sl. No  \n!Type of Visa\n!Period for which granted\n!EntrySingle (S), \nMultiple (M), Double(D)\n!Documents required with application\n!Extendable in India\n|-\n|1\n|Tourist\n|5 years\n|M\n| \u2013 \n|NO\n|-\n|2\n|Transit\n|15 days\n|S/ D\n|Return/ onward journey ticket\n|NO\n|-\n|3\n|Business\n|5 years\n|M\n|Documents to prove bonafide purpose (Company letter etc.)\n|YES\n|-\n|4\n|Employment\n|1 year/ period of contract\n|M\n|Proof of employment (appointment document), terms and conditions\n|YES\n|-\n|5\n|Student\n|Period of course/ 5 years\n|M\n|Proof of admission in Indian Institution\n|YES\n|-\n|6\n|Foreigners of Indian Origin\n|5 years\n|M\n|Proof of being of Indian Origin\n|YES\n|-\n|7\n|Intern\n|Duration of the Internship or One year, whichever is less\n|S/D/M\n|Letter from the Indian company/educational institution/NGO concerned sponsoring the foreign national for internship programme clearly indicating the period of internship.\n|Non-extendable.(Registration required within 14 days of arrival with concerned FRO)\n|-\n|8\n|Film\n|Duration of the shooting of the film as per schedule submitted or One year, whichever is less\n|S/D/M\n|<nowiki>-Copy of detailed shooting script in case of feature film and detailed concept in case of TV show/serial - Details of visiting film crew and location of film shooting. - Letter of intent regarding the shooting of the film in India mentioning the production schedule, particulars of the cast and crew coming to India for the purpose of shoot, chosen location, list of film equipment and other relevant details.</nowiki>\n|YES\n|}\n\n* If visa is for more than 180 days, registration is compulsory within 14 days of arrival in India.<br />\n\n'''Requirement of Identification Papers to Establish Their Identity as Nepalese or Indian for Persons Entering India or Nepal from Either Country by Air'''\n\nInstructions have been issued whereby Nepalese and Indian citizens, while travelling by air, between the two countries must be in possession of any of the following documents to prove their nationality:\n\n* Valid national passport\n* Valid photo identity card issued by the Government of India / State Government or UT Administration / Election Commission of India\n* Emergency certificate issued by the Embassy of India, Kathmandu to Indians and by the Embassy of Nepal in Delhi in respect of Nepalese citizens\n\n'''Stateless persons'''\nSingle entry visa, not exceeding one month, may be granted by the Indian Missions/ Posts to a \nstateless person (other than Afghan, Chinese including Taiwanese, Iranian, Pakistani or Somalian \norigin). In respect of persons of Afghan, Chinese including Taiwanese, Iranian, Pakistani or \nSomalian origin, prior clearance of the Ministry of Home Affairs will be required.\n\n'''Grant of Permanent Residency Status (PRS) to foreign investors'''\nPermanent Residency Status (PRS) will be granted to foreign investors making investment under \nForeign Direct Investment (FDI) route. This scheme will not be applicable to Pakistani citizens \nor third country nationals of Pakistani origin. To be eligible, the foreign investor should invest a \nminimum of Rs. 10 crores to be brought within 18 months or Rs.25 crores to be brought within \n36 months. The foreign investment should result in generating employment to at least 20 resident \nIndians in every financial year. This scheme will be applicable to only foreign investors fulfilling \nthe above mentioned eligibility conditions, his/ her spouse and dependents. Top management \nexecutives will not be covered by this scheme and they will have to come on normal Employment \nVisa.\n\n'''Employment Visa'''\nAn Employment visa is granted to a foreigner who is a highly skilled and/or qualified \nprofessional. Employment Visa shall not be granted \u2013 (i) for jobs for which qualified Indians are \navailable and (ii) for routine, ordinary or secretarial/clerical jobs. Employment visa is not \ngranted to a citizen of Pakistan\n\n'''Re entry permit within two months'''\nTravelers on\u00a0Tourist visasare\u00a0no longer\u00a0required to have a\u00a0gap\u00a0of at least\u00a02 months\u00a0between\u00a0two separate\u00a0visits to India. The exception being: Nationals of China, Iran, Pakistan, Iraq, Sudan, Afghanistan, foreigners of Pakistani origin and stateless persons.\n\n'''Landing permit'''\nA landing permit facility, up to a maximum of three days, can be given to a foreigner \u2013\nwho enters India by air or sea, without a valid visa, under emergent circumstances (like \ndeath or sudden illness in family);  who has arrived in India by air or sea and desires to leave \u2013\n(a) the specified precincts of the airport, or\n(b) the ship during its halt at an Indian port; who has arrived by air and desires to resume his/her journey by the next regularly.\nNo landing permit facility shall be granted to a national of Afghanistan, China, Ethiopia, \nIraq, Nigeria, Pakistan, Somalia & Sri Lanka and foreign nationals of Pakistan origin \neven if he/she is transiting through India and has a confirmed onward journey ticket.\n\n'''e-VISA'''\nEligibility\ne-Visa is granted to a foreigner whose sole objective of visiting India is recreation, sight seeing, \ncasual visit to meet friends or relatives, attending a short term yoga programme, medical \ntreatment including treatment under Indian systems of medicine and business purpose and no \nother purpose/ activity. This facility shall not be available if the person or either of his / her \nparents or grand parents (paternal or maternal) was born in, or was permanently resident in \nPakistan. e-Visa facility shall not be available to holders of Diplomatic/Official passports, UNLP \n(UN Passport) holders and international travel document holders e.g. INTERPOL officials. List \nof countries whose nationals are presently eligible for e-visa is given in Appendix I.\n\n'''VISA-ON-ARRIVAL'''\nEligibility\nVisa-on-Arrival is granted to Japanese, South Korean and Uae national (Only if the Uae national before ever obtained a e visa or regular paper visa) who is visiting India for business, tourism, \nconference and medical purposes. This facility shall not be available to the citizens of Japan if \nthe person or either of his / her parents or grandparents (paternal or maternal) was born in, or was \npermanently resident in Pakistan. This facility shall not be available to holders of \nDiplomatic/Official passports and UN Passport holders having Japanese, South korean and Uae nationality.\n\n'''TRANSIT VISA'''\nEligibility and other conditions\nA transit visa is granted to a foreigner for the sole purpose of enabling him/ her to travel through \nIndia to a destination outside India. A person who desires to make two entries into India in \ntransit in the course of the same journey can be granted a transit visa valid for two entries and for \nstay in transit for a period not exceeding 3 days for each journey.\n\n'''TOURIST VISA'''\nEligibility\nA Tourist visa is granted to a foreigner whose sole objective of visiting India is recreation, sight \nseeing, casual visit to meet friends or relatives, attending a short term yoga programme, short \nduration medical treatment including treatment under Indian systems of medicine etc. and no \nother purpose/ activity. [Short term yoga programme means a yoga programme not exceeding 6\nmonths duration and not issued with a qualifying certificate/ diploma etc.] \nValidity\nValidity of a tourist visa will be as specified below: \nMultiple entry Tourist Visa may be granted for a period of 10 years to the nationals of \nUSA, Canada and Japan with a stipulation that \u201ccontinuous stay during each visit shall \nnot exceed 180 days and registration not required\u201d.\nIn respect of nationals of other countries (except for nationals of 33 countries mentioned \nbelow), Multiple entry Tourist Visa may be granted for a period of 5 years as a default \noption. Grant of 5-year Tourist Visa will be with the stipulation \u201cContinuous stay during \neach visit shall not exceed 90 days and registration not required\u201d. However, in the case of \nnationals of UK, continuous stay during each visit shall not exceed 180 days. \nIn respect of nationals of 30 countries i.e. (1) Iran, (2) Egypt, (3) Libya, (4) Qatar, (5) \nIraq, (6) Syria, (7) Sudan, (8) Tunisia, (9) Kuwait, (10)Yemen, (11) Algeria, \n(12)Bahrain, (13) Turkey, (14) Morocco, (15) Kyrgyzstan, (16) Turkmenistan, (17)Democratic People\u2019s Republic of Korea (North Korea), (18) Lebanon, (19) Afghanistan, \n(20) Saudi Arabia, (21) Uganda, (22) Congo, (23) Ethiopia, (24) Nigeria, (25) Belarus, \n(26) Somalia, (27) South Sudan, (28) Kazakhstan, (29) Uzbekistan and (30) Sri Lanka,\nduration of visa will be decided by the concerned Indian Missions/ Posts subject to a \nmaximum of 5 years with the stipulation \u201ccontinous stay during each visit shall not \nexceed 90 days and registration not required\u201d.\n(iv) In respect of nationals of Bangladesh and China, provisions as available in the bilateral \nagreements/ policy guidelines, as issued from time to time, will be applicable.\n(v) Tourist visa is not available to Pakistan nationals.\n(vi) In the case of foreign nationals of Pakistan origin, Tourist Visa will be granted for a \nperiod of 3 months with single entry.\n\n== Visitor statistics ==\nMost visitors arriving in India were from the following countries of nationality:<ref>[http://tourism.gov.in/market-research-and-statistics Market research and statistics]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Country || 2017 || 2016 || 2015 || 2014 || 2013\n|-\n| {{flag|Bangladesh}} || {{hs|01}} {{increase}} 2,156,557 || {{hs|01}} {{increase}} 1,380,409 || {{hs|02}} {{increase}} 1,133,879 || {{hs|02}} {{increase}} 942,562 || {{hs|03}} {{increase}} 524,923\n|-style=background-color:#DDDDDD;\"\n| {{flag|United States}} || {{hs|02}} {{increase}} 1,376,919 || {{hs|02}} {{increase}} 1,296,939 || {{hs|01}} {{increase}} 1,213,624 || {{hs|01}} {{increase}} 1,118,983 || {{hs|01}} {{increase}} 1,085,309\n|-\n| {{flag|United Kingdom}} || {{hs|03}} {{increase}} 986,296 || {{hs|03}} {{increase}} 941,883 || {{hs|03}} {{increase}} 867,601 || {{hs|03}} {{increase}} 838,860 || {{hs|02}} {{increase}} 809,444\n|-style=background-color:#DDDDDD;\"\n| {{flag|Canada}} || {{hs|04}} {{increase}} 335,439 || {{hs|04}} {{increase}} 317,239 || {{hs|05}} {{increase}} 281,306 || {{hs|06}} {{increase}} 268,485 || {{hs|06}} {{decrease}} 255,222\n|-style=background-color:#DDDDDD;\"\n| {{flag|Australia}} || {{hs|05}}